{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.09,0.2,0.1,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112863"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46085"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112863"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of an itchy rash, mild fever, and numbness. She returned from a two-week holiday in Brazil eight days ago. She has no significant medical history and takes the combined oral contraceptive pill. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has bilateral non-purulent conjunctivitis. There is a blanching maculopapular rash that started on her face and has spread to her trunk and limbs, and involves her palms and soles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Zika virus infection","Dengue fever","Measles","Secondary syphilis","Chikungunya virus infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of Zika virus infection: pruritic maculopapular rash, fever, and non-purulent conjunctivitis. The recent travel history to Brazil, where Zika virus is endemic, strongly supports this diagnosis. The mild nature of symptoms and presence of conjunctivitis are particularly characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003EZika virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E. It is spread by mosquitoes and infection is usually resolved within a week with supportive mangement. Diagnosis is by IgG and IgM serology. Zika virus may be complicated by Guilliain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome and it is associated with congenital abnormalities when pregnant women are infected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more severe symptoms including high fever, severe muscle aches, and severe headache as \u0027break bone fever\u0027. While a rash may occur, it typically appears later in the illness after the fever subsides. Conjunctivitis is not a typical feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChikungunya virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by sudden onset of high fever and severe joint pain that can be debilitating. While a rash may occur, conjunctivitis is not typical, the rash is not pruritic and the arthralgia is usually more severe than seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E typically begins with high fever, cough, coryza, and also presents with conjunctivitis. The rash appears 3-4 days after the onset of fever and spreads from head to feet. Koplik\u0027s spots would be expected early in the illness. The patient\u0027s vaccination status and lack of respiratory symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a widespread maculopapular rash involving the palms and soles of the feet, and mild systemic symptoms. However, the rash is typically non-pruritic, and conjunctivitis is not a feature. The rapid onset and travel history make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Zika virus infection commonly presents with a pruritic micropapular rash that spreads from face to extremities.","Conjunctivitis is a characteristic feature of Zika virus infection that helps distinguish it from other arboviral infections."],"references":["Cordel N, Birembaux X, Chaumont H, et al. Main Characteristics of Zika Virus Exanthema in Guadeloupe. JAMA Dermatol. 2017;153(4):326\u2013328.  Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamadermatology/fullarticle/2604250#google_vignette","Oakley A.  Zika Virus. DermNet NZ.  2016. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/zika-virus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T10:21:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T10:22:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112863"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.e